The centres of the two circles, as discussed in the old post, are $A = (0,1)$ and $B = (3,4)$. Letting $C$ be the centre of the third circle, let $\theta$ be the angle $\angle ACB$, and let $f$ and $g$ be the radii of the circles with centres $A$ and $B$, respectively. Then, as discussed in the previous post, the coordinates of $C$ can be expressed in terms of $\cos(\theta)$ and $\sin(\theta)$:\[C = (g+f)\cos(\theta)-f\textbf{i},(g+f)\sin(\theta)-g\textbf{j},\]where we write $\textbf{i}$ and $\textbf{j}$ for vectors from the origin to $A$ and $B$, respectively. Then pick a point on the common external tangent such that the triangle is isosceles, then we have$$\underbrace{4\textbf{j}}_{\text{From center at }B}\stride\angle{CAQ}\textbf{j},-f\textbf{i},-g\textbf{j}\stride\underbrace{4\textbf{i}+f\textbf{j}}_{\text{From center at }A}.$$After some algebra and applying the law of cosines,$$\cos(\theta) = -\frac{4 + \sqrt{21}}{9},$$so$$\cos(\theta) = \frac{3 + \sqrt{21}}{9},$$$$0.8330302772883$$and similarly$$\sin(\theta) = \frac{\sqrt{18 - 2\sqrt{21}}}{9},$$$$0.55502869665032.$$So the radius of the third circle is$$\frac{g\sin(\theta)}{\sqrt{g^2+f^2 - 2gf\cos(\theta)}} = \frac{3\sqrt{18-2\sqrt{21}}}{\sqrt{25 + 18\sqrt{21}}} = \frac{6\sqrt{21\sqrt{21}-1}}{25}\cdot\dfrac{25}{\sqrt{25+18\sqrt{21}}}\cdot\dfrac{\sqrt{25-18\sqrt{21}}}{\sqrt{25-18\sqrt{21}}} = \sqrt{\frac{2(25-18\sqrt{21})}{25+18\sqrt{21}}}\sqrt{25-18\sqrt{21}},\approx0.1968\cdot1.532\approx0.1968.$$ <answer>$0.1968 (180\sqrt{21-4\sqrt{21}}) : 25$</answer>

